title: The Royal Opera House: Il trovatore
aka: The Royal Opera House: Il trovatore
genres: ['datePublished: 2017-01-27', 'review: {', '@type: Review', 'itemReviewed: {', '@type: CreativeWork', 'url: /title/tt6914234/', '}', 'author: {', '@type: Person', 'name: TheLittleSongbird', '}', 'dateCreated: 2017-10-23', 'inLanguage: English', 'name: Head-scratching', 'reviewBody: \\u0027ll Trovatore\\u0027 as has been said many times before does have a notoriously convoluted story and is over the top dramatically but it is memorable for the character of the gypsy Azucena and for containing one of Verdi\\u0027s most melodically rich score. Even when the stories are not always great Verdi\\u0027s music nearly always delivers.\\n\\nHave seen some great productions of \\u0027Il Trovatore\\u0027 a primary example being the brilliant 2015 Met production which was not only perfect musically but also solved all the potential problems that the opera has when it comes to being staged. It is an opera that is better served on record though. This Royal Opera House Covent Garden production is not one of them. Along with their \\u0027Guillaume Tell\\u0027 it is one of the weaker Royal Opera House Live Cinema transmissions (hugely disappointing after being blown away by the house\\u0027s \\u0027The Nutcracker\\u0027 just over a month previously). It is also one of the ugliest productions of \\u0027Il Trovatore\\u0027 visually and staging-wise it is one of the most puzzling and least compelling.\\n\\nThere is not much here that works but some things do. The best thing about the production is Anita Rachvelishvili who may not quite surpass Dolora Zajick as the best Azucena of the past thirty years or so but is truly magnificent in the role. She may be helped by that Azucena is the most interesting and plausible character in \\u0027Il Trovatore\\u0027 but a lot of it is also to do with that she has a thrilling dark rich sound to her voice and is both formidable and affecting always riveting dramatically. Not many mezzos nail \\Stride La Vampa\\ Rachvelishvili manages that feat.\\n\\nLianna Haroutounian has the nobility pathos and strength for Leonora and vocally it is some of the best singing personally heard from her what she may lack in a trill she makes up for a lovely sound that overcomes the hurdles of the role capably (\\D\\u0027Amor Sull\\u0027Alli Rosee\\ is very deeply felt). Vitaliy Bilyy has some under-powered and coarse moments as Di Luna mainly in the middle-lower registers in ensembles but his voice does have a lot of authority and sonority and he really does try to make Di Luna (a pretty unsubtly stock role) more than a villain.\\n\\nAlexander Tsymbalyuk makes one want to listen to his dark tale while Francesca Chiejina\\u0027s Ines is touching and sympathetic and Samuel Sakker\\u0027s Ruiz is sturdy enough. The male chorus are well blended and commanding and the orchestra do make a real effort to bring out the power and intimacy of the score though there is a lack of nuance and the tempos don\\u0027t excite or move.\\n\\nOn the other hand Gregory Kunde fails to bring heroism or dimension to Manrico and his acting is rather stolid and rudimentary one can expect it from the 1940s and 1950s but with acting in opera having come on enormously over the years one really does expect so much more. Vocally he starts off strong but from \\Di Quella Pira\\ onward he sounds taxed losing the initial ring and becomes strained instead musicality is not a strong suit with too much of a loud dynamic and phrasing is not so refined. He has very little romantic chemistry with Haroutounian although just about convincing with Rachvelishvili and although I do refrain to bring up ages for reviewing opera it is hard not to in this case because Kunde just looks far too old to pass for a romantic lead when he is old enough to be both Haroutounian and Rachvelishvili\\u0027s father it really stretches credibility.\\n\\nDespite the orchestra faring quite well the conducting is far too routine and frequently lacks energy thrills and poetry. It is never alert to the drama and rarely accommodates the singers.\\n\\nVisually and in the stage direction it\\u0027s in these areas where this \\u0027Il Trovatore\\u0027 fails. The production is really ugly visually it looks cheap and drab constantly and not only distracts from the drama but swamps it (one of opera stage direction\\u0027s biggest crimes in my opinion). Rarely has costumes in an opera production looked so schlocky. David Bösch\\u0027s stage direction makes very little attempt to make the drama clearer character motivations more plausible and more interesting in an opera that despite amazing music really cries out for those things to happen.\\n\\nApart from moments in Act 2 it\\u0027s dull lacks cohesion and frequently fights against the libretto any initial attempts made to do any of those things are wasted when there is a real sense of giving up halfway through when things get even more aimless and weirder. Despite good singing the chorus are over-directed and come over as far too camp.\\n\\nOverall has moments especially Azucena but unattractive and head-scratching. 4/10 Bethany Cox', 'reviewRating: {', '@type: Rating', 'worstRating: 1', 'bestRating: 10', 'ratingValue: 4', '}', '}', 'duration: PT3H', 'trailer: {', '@type: VideoObject', 'name: Official Trailer', 'embedUrl: /video/imdb/vi3063202073', 'thumbnail: {', '@type: ImageObject', 'contentUrl: https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BMGZkODJhM2MtOTdmNy00MTBhLWIyY2ItNzZmYzQ0ZDJiMDM3XkEyXkFqcGdeQXRyYW5zY29kZS13b3JrZmxvdw@@._V1_.jpg', '}', 'thumbnailUrl: https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BMGZkODJhM2MtOTdmNy00MTBhLWIyY2ItNzZmYzQ0ZDJiMDM3XkEyXkFqcGdeQXRyYW5zY29kZS13b3JrZmxvdw@@._V1_.jpg', 'uploadDate: 2020-09-28T10:19:12Z', '}']

title: Royal Opera House Live Cinema Season 2016/17: Woolf Works
genres: ['datePublished: 2017-03-31', 'review: {', '@type: Review', 'itemReviewed: {', '@type: CreativeWork', 'url: /title/tt6728386/', '}', 'author: {', '@type: Person', 'name: TheLittleSongbird', '}', 'dateCreated: 2017-10-24', 'inLanguage: English', 'name: Virginia Woolf in ballet form', 'reviewBody: Virginia Woolf was a very interesting (one of the most interesting of the 20th century as a woman as well as a writer) insightful influential (in her unique use of narrative devices) and inspiring writer and still is deserving of that reputation even if her critical views on feminism were more controversial.\\n\\n\\u0027Woolf Works\\u0027 had the truly ambitious task of adapting two of Woolf\\u0027s best known works \\u0027Mrs Dalloway\\u0027 and \\u0027Orlando\\u0027 and also \\u0027The Waves\\u0027 in ballet form with any of Woolf\\u0027s work being adapted in any form being daunting enough let alone for ballet. It succeeds and brilliantly in by far one of the best and most fascinating experiences of \\new discovery\\ ballets personally seen (an earlier new discovery being the uneven but still intriguing \\u0027Anastasia\\u0027 both in production and the ballet itself). It may not be one of my favourite ballets any time soon but do not regret in any way watching it.\\n\\nIt doesn\\u0027t work completely. It is at its weakest in the \\u0027Orlando\\u0027 segment. It is visually striking and Natalia Osipova gives a dynamic performance that has swagger as well. The things that work against it are the choreography that is neither playful or moving enough and the acting of the rest of the dancers which came over as too cold.\\n\\n\\u0027Mrs Dalloway\\u0027 and \\u0027The Waves\\u0027 fare much better. While the very atmospheric and visually stunning \\u0027The Waves\\u0027 is a little better visually \\u0027Mrs Dalloway\\u0027 is the best when it comes to the choreography drama and dancing. \\u0027The Waves\\u0027 is truly haunting and has plenty of nuance and emotional power but \\u0027Mrs Dalloway\\u0027 is just exquisite not just the nuanced and multi-layered acting and dancing but also the drama moved me to tears.\\n\\nCan\\u0027t fault a vast majority of the dancing the dramatic coldness of most of the dancers (excepting Osipova) being the only weak spot. The best performances are in \\u0027Mrs Dalloway\\u0027. Alessandra Ferri looks wonderful and dances a dream at 53 years old and her interpretation haunts the mind in its delicacy. Beatriz Stix-Brunell is tenderly touching and Edward Watson is heart-wrenching in his grief.\\n\\nOn the choreography front only the lack of playfulness and poignancy disappoints. In \\u0027The Waves\\u0027 and particularly \\u0027Mrs Dalloway\\u0027 it is hugely intelligent and nuanced to the maximum and fully captures the spirit of the works the ballet is based on.\\n\\nWhen it comes to the music Max Richter\\u0027s score will never be one of my favourites but it has many moments of beauty and power it has the sympathetic edge needed for the choreography and drama on stage and doesn\\u0027t work against it. The Woolf excerpts were thought-provoking and moving as well as treated with respect.\\n\\nSumming up truly fascinating and often beautiful. Just wish that the \\u0027Orlando\\u0027 segment lived up to the rest of the production. 8/10 Bethany Cox', 'reviewRating: {', '@type: Rating', 'worstRating: 1', 'bestRating: 10', 'ratingValue: 8', '}', '}']
